## Problem
When using SceneCapture2D for single-frame screenshots, the captured image is extremely dark/black compared to the editor viewport.

## Root Cause
SceneCapture2D with auto-exposure (default) needs multiple frames for eye adaptation to converge. When capturing only a single frame, the auto-exposure starts from a default state and hasn't had time to adapt to the scene brightness, resulting in severely underexposed images.

## Solution
Override the auto-exposure method to `AEM_Manual` on the SceneCaptureComponent2D's PostProcessSettings:

```cpp
// Force manual exposure to avoid single-frame adaptation issue
CaptureComp->PostProcessSettings.bOverride_AutoExposureMethod = true;
CaptureComp->PostProcessSettings.AutoExposureMethod = EAutoExposureMethod::AEM_Manual;

// Set exposure bias from viewport's FixedEV100
CaptureComp->PostProcessSettings.bOverride_AutoExposureBias = true;
CaptureComp->PostProcessSettings.AutoExposureBias = ExposureBias;

// Ensure post-process overrides take effect
CaptureComp->PostProcessBlendWeight = 1.0f;
```

## Key Notes
- `SCS_FinalColorLDR` is the correct CaptureSource for matching viewport output
- The viewport's `ExposureSettings.FixedEV100` (default 1.0) provides a good baseline exposure value
- If the viewport uses auto-exposure (bFixed=false), the FixedEV100 still works as a reasonable default
- PostProcessVolume settings in the scene will still be picked up by SceneCapture

## Problem
SceneCapture2D produces screenshots with incorrect colors/exposure compared to the editor viewport. Even with manual exposure overrides (AEM_Manual, fixed EV100), the result doesn't match the viewport's final rendering because SceneCapture2D fundamentally re-renders the scene with its own rendering pipeline state.

## Root Cause (First Principles)
SceneCapture2D creates a NEW render pass — it's not reading the existing viewport's frame buffer. It re-renders the scene from scratch, which means:
- Auto-exposure can't converge in a single frame
- PostProcess settings may differ
- No amount of parameter tweaking can perfectly replicate the viewport's multi-frame converged state

## Solution
Don't re-render. Instead, directly read the viewport's already-rendered frame buffer:

```cpp
// 1. Switch to GameView to hide gizmo/grid/icons
const bool bWasInGameView = ViewClient.IsInGameView();
if (!bWasInGameView) ViewClient.SetGameView(true);

// 2. Force viewport to redraw one frame (update frame buffer without presenting)
Viewport->Invalidate();
Viewport->Draw(false); // false = don't present to screen
FlushRenderingCommands();

// 3. Read the final rendered pixels directly
TArray<FColor> Bitmap;
Viewport->ReadPixels(Bitmap);

// 4. Restore GameView state
if (!bWasInGameView) { ViewClient.SetGameView(false); Viewport->Invalidate(); }

// 5. Resize if needed
if (ViewWidth != TargetWidth || ViewHeight != TargetHeight)
    FImageUtils::ImageResize(ViewWidth, ViewHeight, Bitmap, TargetWidth, TargetHeight, ResizedBitmap, true);
```

## Key Insight
The viewport ALREADY has the correct final rendering. The only task is to READ it, not to RECREATE it.
